### GitHub Vulnerability Alerts

#### [CVE-2025-24964](https://redirect.github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/security/advisories/GHSA-9crc-q9x8-hgqq)

### Summary
Arbitrary remote Code Execution when accessing a malicious website while Vitest API server is listening by Cross-site WebSocket hijacking (CSWSH) attacks.

### Details
When [`api` option](https://vitest.dev/config/#api) is enabled (Vitest UI enables it), Vitest starts a WebSocket server. This WebSocket server did not check Origin header and did not have any authorization mechanism and was vulnerable to CSWSH attacks.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L32-L46

This WebSocket server has `saveTestFile` API that can edit a test file and `rerun` API that can rerun the tests. An attacker can execute arbitrary code by injecting a code in a test file by the `saveTestFile` API and then running that file by calling the `rerun` API.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L66-L76

### PoC
1. Open Vitest UI.
2. Access a malicious web site with the script below.
3. If you have `calc` executable in `PATH` env var (you'll likely have it if you are running on Windows), that application will be executed.

opened_issues.title: Suggestion: Add platform interface to core package for eliza v2
opened_issues.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

This is a problem in that I'm trying to build a platform agnostic core package but eliza has no way of injecting specific platforms into it. It also seems like I will have to pollyfill some node.js libraries to use elizav2 core package

**Describe the solution you'd like**

V2 is super clean but it really needs a platform abstraction. 

```typescript
interface Platform {
  name: string
  readFile?: typeof fs.readFile
  ...etc
}

class NodePlatform implements Platform {
  name: 'NODEJS'
  readFile fs.readFile
  ..etc
} 
```

Such that now 
- the entire core package has no platform specific logic in it. Less complexity
- no imports (except typescript types)  in core package reference a node.js module. No need to polyfill
- Flexible to provide our own platform for say bun if bun has a node incompatability causing issue in eliza or being in the browser but emulating a file system, etc.

This is a common pattern in other libraries such as [effect.ts](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/tree/main/packages/platform)

opened_issues.title: Enhancement: Improve TwitterPostClient dry run functionality
opened_issues.body:
Please note: You'll find me happy to implement this change once approved. It'd be my first open-source contribution!

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

The TwitterPostClient's dry run mode currently only logs tweet content via elizaLogger.info() without returning the data. This makes it difficult to programmatically access draft tweets, requiring workarounds like runtime method overriding. Specifically, applications need to override the info logger at runtime to capture the draft tweet content, which is brittle and hard to maintain.

**Describe the solution you'd like**

Modify the generateNewTweet() method to return a structured result object while maintaining existing logging behavior:

```typescript
interface TweetGenerationResult {
  success: boolean;
  dryRun?: boolean;
  tweet?: string;
  error?: string;
}
```

This would allow applications to programmatically access draft tweets while maintaining backwards compatibility through continued logging.

`isDryRun`'s current `return` in `main`: https://github.com/elizaOS/eliza/blob/81a35281b93d5e8ca0745e9d13a1943e9a90681b/packages/client-twitter/src/post.ts#L605-L610

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

- Runtime method overriding (current workaround)
- Creating a separate dryRun method
- Using events to emit draft tweets

The structured return object provides the cleanest solution with the least impact on existing code.

Again, you'd find me happy to implement this change.

**Additional context**

This enhancement would improve the developer experience when building applications on top of the client-twitter package. The current implementation forces developers to use workarounds that make code harder to maintain and test.

Our team developed a service to manage agent RagKnowledge, it interacts with the RagKnowledge instance under agent runtime directly

#### [CVE-2025-24964](https://redirect.github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/security/advisories/GHSA-9crc-q9x8-hgqq)

### Summary
Arbitrary remote Code Execution when accessing a malicious website while Vitest API server is listening by Cross-site WebSocket hijacking (CSWSH) attacks.

### Details
When [`api` option](https://vitest.dev/config/#api) is enabled (Vitest UI enables it), Vitest starts a WebSocket server. This WebSocket server did not check Origin header and did not have any authorization mechanism and was vulnerable to CSWSH attacks.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L32-L46

This WebSocket server has `saveTestFile` API that can edit a test file and `rerun` API that can rerun the tests. An attacker can execute arbitrary code by injecting a code in a test file by the `saveTestFile` API and then running that file by calling the `rerun` API.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L66-L76

### PoC
1. Open Vitest UI.
2. Access a malicious web site with the script below.
3. If you have `calc` executable in `PATH` env var (you'll likely have it if you are running on Windows), that application will be executed.

### GitHub Vulnerability Alerts

#### [CVE-2025-24964](https://redirect.github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/security/advisories/GHSA-9crc-q9x8-hgqq)

### Summary
Arbitrary remote Code Execution when accessing a malicious website while Vitest API server is listening by Cross-site WebSocket hijacking (CSWSH) attacks.

### Details
When [`api` option](https://vitest.dev/config/#api) is enabled (Vitest UI enables it), Vitest starts a WebSocket server. This WebSocket server did not check Origin header and did not have any authorization mechanism and was vulnerable to CSWSH attacks.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L32-L46

This WebSocket server has `saveTestFile` API that can edit a test file and `rerun` API that can rerun the tests. An attacker can execute arbitrary code by injecting a code in a test file by the `saveTestFile` API and then running that file by calling the `rerun` API.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L66-L76

### PoC
1. Open Vitest UI.
2. Access a malicious web site with the script below.
3. If you have `calc` executable in `PATH` env var (you'll likely have it if you are running on Windows), that application will be executed.

Feature

### GitHub Vulnerability Alerts

#### [CVE-2025-24964](https://redirect.github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/security/advisories/GHSA-9crc-q9x8-hgqq)

### Summary
Arbitrary remote Code Execution when accessing a malicious website while Vitest API server is listening by Cross-site WebSocket hijacking (CSWSH) attacks.

### Details
When [`api` option](https://vitest.dev/config/#api) is enabled (Vitest UI enables it), Vitest starts a WebSocket server. This WebSocket server did not check Origin header and did not have any authorization mechanism and was vulnerable to CSWSH attacks.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L32-L46

This WebSocket server has `saveTestFile` API that can edit a test file and `rerun` API that can rerun the tests. An attacker can execute arbitrary code by injecting a code in a test file by the `saveTestFile` API and then running that file by calling the `rerun` API.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L66-L76

### PoC
1. Open Vitest UI.
2. Access a malicious web site with the script below.
3. If you have `calc` executable in `PATH` env var (you'll likely have it if you are running on Windows), that application will be executed.

### GitHub Vulnerability Alerts

#### [CVE-2025-24964](https://redirect.github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/security/advisories/GHSA-9crc-q9x8-hgqq)

### Summary
Arbitrary remote Code Execution when accessing a malicious website while Vitest API server is listening by Cross-site WebSocket hijacking (CSWSH) attacks.

### Details
When [`api` option](https://vitest.dev/config/#api) is enabled (Vitest UI enables it), Vitest starts a WebSocket server. This WebSocket server did not check Origin header and did not have any authorization mechanism and was vulnerable to CSWSH attacks.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L32-L46

This WebSocket server has `saveTestFile` API that can edit a test file and `rerun` API that can rerun the tests. An attacker can execute arbitrary code by injecting a code in a test file by the `saveTestFile` API and then running that file by calling the `rerun` API.
https://github.com/vitest-dev/vitest/blob/9a581e1c43e5c02b11e2a8026a55ce6a8cb35114/packages/vitest/src/api/setup.ts#L66-L76

### PoC
1. Open Vitest UI.
2. Access a malicious web site with the script below.
3. If you have `calc` executable in `PATH` env var (you'll likely have it if you are running on Windows), that application will be executed.

# Relates to
Initial implementation of Perplexity AI plugin

# Risks
Low - This is a new plugin that doesn't affect existing functionality.
- API key security needs to be properly handled
- Rate limiting needs to be respected

# Background

## What does this PR do?
Adds a new plugin for Perplexity AI integration, providing:
- Text generation
- Sentiment analysis 
- Content moderation
- Text editing capabilities
- Structured output support

## What kind of change is this?
Features (non-breaking change which adds functionality)

# Documentation changes needed?
My changes require a change to the project documentation.
- Need to add Perplexity plugin documentation
- Need to document environment variables (PERPLEXITY_API_KEY)
- Need to document dependency on @elizaos/core

# Testing

## Where should a reviewer start?
1. Add @elizaos/core dependency
2. Review `src/actions/generateTextAction.ts` as the primary action
3. Review `src/types.ts` for API interface definitions
4. Review `src/actions/action.ts` for shared utilities

## Detailed testing steps
1. Install dependencies:
```bash
npm install @elizaos/core
```

2. Set up PERPLEXITY_API_KEY in environment

3. Run basic text generation:
```typescript
const result = await generateTextAction.handler(runtime, "Write a hello world message", {});
console.log(result.text);
```

4. Test sentiment analysis:
```typescript
const result = await analyzeSentimentAction.handler(runtime, "This is amazing!");
console.log(result.text); // Should return JSON with sentiment and confidence
```

5. Verify error handling for unsupported features (embeddings, transcription)

# Deploy Notes
- Requires PERPLEXITY_API_KEY environment variable
- Requires @elizaos/core dependency
- Compatible with existing OpenAI client libraries
- No database changes required

_marsic
